				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">PS. Cyricus, I bet it felt good to say that. I think you've been holding that in for a very long time. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
Not really. I don't get any satisfaction from quasi-ranting when i am desperate. Let me clear something up: I like this game. If i didn't like it i wouldn't have played it for so long and invest so much time into my character, this board and class balance. However i foresee people i played with for years leaving if this new expansion fails to brings back the "spirit" of Everquest. There are so many great ideas posted on every major classboard that it should be easy to create something everyone will want to play. I mean that it would be really easy to draw more players to EQ if the new expansion offers (based on what i read on various boards and my own ideas):
<br />

<br />
<span style="text-decoration: underline">Lore:</span>
<br />

<br />
Now when i say lore i don't mean this soulles being called Morden Rasp and his muppet show who label themselves the Wayfarer Brotherhood, but characters that are introduced with GM events. They need to appear often, they need to show a personality people want to remember instead of ignoring them. You all remember Al'Kabor for example. Showed up quite often, spells are named after him, special GM event items were handed out not only to the high end raiders but to whoever was able to reach him first (during the Luclin introduction). Hell, you all remember Trilith Magi'Kot by following his path when getting your Mage Epic. His ultimate failure is still remembered by everyone who started the quest and that is because EVERY npc added to the story. Lore is the central element of every good RPG. 
<br />

<br />
Now with LDoN i still ask myself why i need to help the Wayfarer Brotherhood. Just because the guy suddenly appears out of nowhere and wants me to do a million dumb adventures who are all the same for some silly charm? Btw: I still don't get the idea for charms... why do they get more powerful the more adventures i complete? 
<br />

<br />
Anyway, the same goes for GoD... again Morden shows up, babbles something about a new continent (which was mysteriously hidden for years *cough*) and expects everyone to follow him to free some guys from some other guys who are evil *yawn*. Now you cannot even remember their names, because apparently new characters (and zones) need to have a tongue-twister like name. If i cannot remember a name, if it isn't even made clear from the start why i need to do something (via a climatic event or a series of small events - like GM apparences (which comes with a reward / title)) the story becomes a meaningless. We don't want that, do we?
<br />

<br />

<br />

<br />
<span style="text-decoration: underline">AI:</span>
<br />

<br />
Seriously, what changed when it comes to fighting npc's during all the years you guys played EQ? Right, nothing. It is still the same old concept of the Tank getting aggro, the rest positioning themselves for nukes/heals, (for Luclin+ : some kiters getting ready to kite some possible adds), debuffing and owning. Do this for 5 years and the game gets boring. Improve the AI. Have it adapt to a certain situation. I mean which God for example (with an IQ greater than that of any player) is so dumb to accept being cornered while the rogues happily backstab him?:roll: Now instead of being happy to get backstabbed have him desperately trying to reach a friend, let him make zonewide emotes crying for help against the mortals who dare to fight him, have his friends who suddenly teleport in shield him and cover him from the most damaging attacks (naturally they all use emotes during this fight) etc... Or another example: The mob AI recognizes Fire to be the most used spell on him during the fight, wizards and mages cast spell after spell. So what is our little god doing? Exactly, he will raise a magical shield against Fire so playes need to adapt and change spells / tactics. Let that happen every  few minutes. The same can be applied to certain types of weapons. Make the fights interesting, make them a little bit different every time you try them.
<br />

<br />

<br />
<span style="text-decoration: underline">Spells:</span>
<br />

<br />
Since Kunark there was no real creativity when it comes to spells. Just adding a few more illusions or introducing Burnout XXXVI  with a new name isn't fun. For more info read what i posted before.
<br />

<br />

<br />
<span style="text-decoration: underline">AAs:</span>
<br />

<br />
Again. There are so many great ideas posted all over the net that you only need to spend some time reading to add some creativity here in this area.
<br />

<br />

<br />

<br />
I could go on, but that wouldn't do any good. Everything SOE needs for a good expansion is there if they would just listen. By listening i don't mean PR gags like the Guild Summit which only exists to influence a large audience of players (Top Guilds and EQ related News Boards can do that quite easily), but actively posting on the various class boards. Commenting on new ideas. Discussing and explaining why the idea isn't a good one for example. Constructive feedback never hurt. 
<br />

<br />
Damn, i don't want GoD to be the last expansion i play before moving on to another game.</span><span class="gensmall"><br /><br />Last edited by Cyricus Bloodbane on Fri Jun 04, 2004 4:56 pm; edited 1 time in total</span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
